-- China, South Korea, Indonesia, Philippines: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview
-- V. Ramakrishnan
-- 2010-07-18T22:06:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-18/china-south-korea-indonesia-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html

          
          
             The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  
 Japan: Japan’s financial markets will be closed for a
public holiday.  
 The yield on the 1.1 percent government bond due June 2020
was at 1.085 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  
 The yen traded at 86.61 per dollar at 7:54a.m. in Sydney.  
 China: Agricultural Development Bank will sell 10 billion
yuan ($1.5 billion) of seven-year bonds today.  
 The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.53 percent. The yuan was at 6.7750 per dollar.  
 Indonesia:  The government will sell 5-, 10- and 20-year
Sukuks tomorrow. It will also sell 1-year treasury bills.  
 The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
8.14 percent, according to Inter Dealer Market Association. The
rupiah was at 9,048 per dollar.  
 Malaysia: The government will sell 1 billion ringgit ($312
million) of 182-day Islamic notes today. The central bank will
sell 1.5 billion ringgit of 364-day notes today.  
 The yield on the 3.835 percent debt maturing in August 2015
was 3.36 percent, according to Bursa Malaysia. The ringgit was
at 3.2055.  
 Philippines: The central bank will publish balance of
payments data for June today. The country recorded a surplus of
$388 million in May.  
 The yield on the 7.75 percent debt due February 2020 was
7.60 percent. The peso was at 46.285.  
 Singapore: The government will sell S$3.6 billion ($2.6
billion) of 91-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.25 percent notes due September 2020 was
2.29 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.3785.  
 South Korea: The central bank will sell 1 trillion won
($832 billion) of 91-day bonds, 1.5 trillion won of 28-day bonds
and 400 billion won of 182-day bonds today. The government will
sell 1.5 trillion won of 10-year bonds.  
 The yield on the 4.50 percent bond due in March 2015 was
4.48 percent. The won was at 1,200.90.  
 Thailand: The government will sell 2 billion baht ($62
million) of 28-day bills and 4 billion baht each of 91-day and
182-day bills today.  
 The yield on the 3.625 percent debt due in May 2015 was
3.02 percent. The baht was at 32.24.  
